<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=100765122675802></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f100765122675802><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100765122675802>One of the best (and most underutilized) for XP in the game:</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=12&mid=100765122675802#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=87397><span id= >sniffynifty</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>6 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Dec 6th 10:07 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>For every mage that's from level 20 to 24, I strongly suggest the Hermit in South Karana as your choice leveling spot.&nbsp;&nbsp;Benefits of camping the Hermit are:<br><br>- Great XP from the Hermit at level 20-24 (The Hermit himself is level 20).  You can also get XP from level 25-27, I believe, but it's not as good.<br>- The Hermit himself is not a tough fight at level 20 (casts small Ranger spells and melees for 42 damage).<br>- The Hermit sometimes drops fine steel weapons!<br>- The Hermit is not often camped (On my server anyways).<br>- Best part of all is, the Hermit has a 3-minute spawn time, which you, as a mage, should be able to keep up with consistently.<br><br>Directions for camping the Hermit:<br><br>First, you have to find him.  <br><br>The Hermit's house is southeast from the entrance to Paw (gnoll spires) and is due south from the centaur stables.  The location is approximately N5300, N2300.  From the outside, it looks like a circular stone wall with a wooden gate.  Inside the circular wall is a house, with the Hermit in the back.<br><br>Second, you need to find a good spot to med.  <br><br>I suggest that you med a short distance outside the stone wall, facing the house.  DO NOT med inside the walls.  There are occasional Tesch Mas Gnolls (level 26-30 and KoS) that run from the spires, and one of their paths is directly through the Hermit's house.  If you med within the walls and the Gnoll meets up with you, it will kill you.  I've had this happen to me more than once.  <br><br>Third, you need to target him.  <br><br>This isn't as easy as it sounds, because he's inside a locked house, and you, as a mage, can't pick locks.  There are several methods to targeting him however.  First, you need to park your pet at your medding spot, then walk through the gate.  Do one of the three:<br><br>1: say &quot;kill you&quot; towards the back of the house so that the Hermit can hear you.  This will make him KoS to you and attack you.<br>2: Click on him through the crack in between the door and the wall.  You can just barely see him through this crack.<br>3: Type in &quot;/target a_hermit&quot; towards the back of the house.  I haven't tried this myself.<br><br>I found that Method 2 worked the best, I killed the Hermit at least 100 times and I never had to open his door.<br><br>Fourth, you need to fight him.  <br><br>Pet choice:<br>Some suggest the Earth pet because he has the most hit points, and he can Root the hermit when you're casting on him.  Some suggest the Air pet because it has the most AC and lasts the longest in a brawl, and some suggest the Water pet because it regenerates the fastest, and keeps up better with the Hermit's rapid spawn time.  I say, take your pick, but if you are between level 20 and 24, don't pick Fire!  The hermit will kill your Fire pet very quickly and a mage without a pet is very vulnerable.  Also I suggest repeatedly summoning until you get a &quot;Max Pet&quot;. (you know what I mean)  Burnout and Damage Shield him as always.<br><br>Pulling him:<br>I suggest that after you target him, walk back to where you parked your pet, and pull him with Burst of Flame.  He'll run out of his house and start to attack you.  I suggested Burst of Flame because it generates little aggro and your pet can easily taunt him off you once he starts attacking.  If he starts by casting spells on you, use the &quot;/pet back off&quot; command to prevent him from running into the house and messing things up.<br><br>Killing him:<br>Send your pet, wait for it to say &quot;Taunting Attacker Master&quot; (important!) then cast your Bolt of Flame at him.  Now wait for &quot;Taunting Attacker Master&quot; TWICE then Bolt of Flame him again.  Also, if a Bolt does enough damage to set the Hermit running, go ahead and cast it.  The reason you want the pet to taunt before nuking is that the Hermit will run after YOU if you make him too angry.  If your pet can't taunt him off you quickly, you're as good as dead.  Again, I've learned this the hard way.  If you have trouble with aggro management, I suggest using the Earth pet, its root will keep you a bit safer.<br><br>Now that you've killed him (hopefully), you can med up outside the house until he pops again.  Conveniently, he casts Thistlecoat on himself when he pops so you'll know when to close your spellbook and resume the fight.  Repeat as necessary for some very good XP. :)<br><br>I hope that some of you try this camp and find it helpful.<br><br>Rascarcapac, level 51 Elementalist, Xev Server.<br><br><em id=fs8>Edited, Thu Dec  6 10:08:53 2001</em><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
