	   <tr><td colspan=2>The only monster pets I have ever been able to identify are the fire based pets, since they won't take a fire shield, their own being much better.&nbsp;&nbsp;None of the others have ever cast any sort of ds, let alone cast any sort of spell at all!!!  <br><br>I got the spell at 34 and am now 38 and have been using MS pets almost exclusively since then.  Have used them in the Rathe Mtns against clops, skellies and hill giants but very quickly changed back to normal focus-summoned pets, as their comparative lack of hps and very slow heal rate mean I spend more mana healing my pets than I do in killing.  Particularly against HGs which hit very hard.  However in SK versus gnolls, avocets, harriers; in NK versus the various griffs; and in Iceclad versus snow cougars and dervishes, they are just as effective as the focus pets.  And heaps more fun.  Had a griffon pet in NK and I teamed with a druid to take Grimfeather down.  Half the zone came to watch the battle of the giant griffs - griff pets are about half as big again as normal griffs...<br><br>As far as weapons go, I used to equip mine with swords once, but don't bother now as they seem to make no difference to the pet's ability to hit or speed of attack.  Attacks per round - my first griff pet (the first MS pet I ever cast) got 6 attacks in on one round against a scythe beetle.  I was stunned and elated, but have never been able to reproduce that  :(   Three attacks plus a kick or bash per round are not unusual though, the three attacks probably taking the place of a normal pet's two attacks and a spell cast.<br><br>Bottom line for me now is if I am going up against anything with a LOT of hitpoints, I use a focus pet for its superior heal ability.  If not, I use a MS pet for the fun value  :)  Not looking forward to 39 and going back to normal pets, though I have found and bought MS2 in anticipation.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
